editorialDecl.p: EEBO-TCP is a partnership between the Universities of Michigan and Oxford and the publisher ProQuest to create accurately transcribed and encoded texts based on the image sets published by ProQuest via their Early English Books Online (EEBO) database (http://eebo.chadwyck.com). The general aim of EEBO-TCP is to encode one copy (usually the first edition) of every monographic English-language title published between 1473 and 1700 available in EEBO.

EEBO-TCP aimed to produce large quantities of textual data within the usual project restraints of time and funding, and therefore chose to create diplomatic transcriptions (as opposed to critical editions) with light-touch, mainly structural encoding based on the Text Encoding Initiative (http://www.tei-c.org).

The EEBO-TCP project was divided into two phases. The 25,368 texts created during Phase 1 of the project (2000-2009), initially available only to institutions that contributed to their creation, were released into the public domain on 1 January 2015. The approximately 40,000 texts produced during Phase 2 (2009- ), of which 34,963 had been released as of 2020, originally similarly restricted, were similarly freed from all restrictions on 1 August 2020. As of that date anyone is free to take and use these texts for any purpose (modify them, annotate them, distribute them, etc.). But we do respectfully request that due credit and attribution be given to their original source.
Users should be aware of the process of creating the TCP texts, and therefore of any assumptions that can be made about the data.

Text selection was based on the New Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature (NCBEL). If an author (or for an anonymous work, the title) appears in NCBEL, then their works are eligible for inclusion. Selection was intended to range over a wide variety of subject areas, to reflect the true nature of the print record of the period. In general, first editions of a works in English were prioritized, although there are a number of works in other languages, notably Latin and Welsh, included and sometimes a second or later edition of a work was chosen if there was a compelling reason to do so.

Image sets were sent to external keying companies for transcription and basic encoding. Quality assurance was then carried out by editorial teams in Oxford and Michigan. 5% (or 5 pages, whichever is the greater) of each text was proofread for accuracy and those which did not meet QA standards were returned to the keyers to be redone. After proofreading, the encoding was enhanced and/or corrected and characters marked as illegible were corrected where possible up to a limit of 100 instances per text. Any remaining illegibles were encoded as <gap>s. Understanding these processes should make clear that, while the overall quality of TCP data is very good, some errors will remain and some readable characters will be marked as illegible. Users should bear in mind that in all likelihood such instances will never have been looked at by a TCP editor.
The texts were encoded and linked to page images in accordance with level 4 of the TEI in Libraries guidelines.

Copies of the texts have been issued variously as SGML (TCP schema; ASCII text with mnemonic sdata character entities); displayable XML (TCP schema; characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or text strings within braces); or lossless XML (TEI P5, characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or TEI g elements).
Keying and markup guidelines are available at the Text Creation Partnership web site.

div.p: A REGISTER OF THE Doctors of Phyſick In Our Two UNIVERSITIES OF Cambridge and Oxford.

div.head: TO THE READER.
div.p:
MY Deſign is not in the leaſt to reflect upon the Learned and Regular Phyſicians of the College, whom I ſincerely honour for their Judgment and Integrity, but to lay open the Ignorance and Fraud of a certain Cabal, who have crept into that Society by indirect or baſe means, and do every where boaſt among the Ignorant, that they are Members of the College, while they are the diſgrace and reproach of it, and have nothing elſe to value themſelves upon, but their fooliſh cracking, the College, the College, and I am of the College, at the expence of its Honour and Reputation. Some of theſe have been Fanatick Preachers, Splitters of Cauſes, Servingmen, and Mechanicks, who never well underſtood the Firſt Rudiments of Learning, and yet by their Impudence and Tricks, under the Cover of ſome Foreign Prince or Embaſſador (one diſguiſing his Name by an Out-Landiſh Pronunciation, another Writing it in Latin, for fear of being known) or by ſome Mandate ſurreptitiouſly procured, have ſtolen the Degree of Doctor from our Univerſities; whilſt
others fly beyond Sea to ſome Foreign Univerſity, and there obtain that Degree by the powerful perſwaſive of Money, which their Ignorance was uncapable of at Home, and then they return as wiſe as they went, adorned with the Fine Flumes of a Traveller and a Doctor. Theſe are the moſt arrogant Pretenders, who would engroſs to themſelves all the Knowledge and Practice of Phyſick, whilſt they do not know ſo much as the Names of Diſeaſes, and much leſs the Virtues of Medicines; and yet they ſtrut and ſwagger with the Name of the College, as if that were a ſufficient Charm to Qualifie them for that Noble Profeſſion of Phyſick; and ſuperciliouſly deſpiſe all others, even thoſe who have been Regularly admitted Doctors in our own Univerſities, as Quacks and Mountebancks, whom themſelves do ſo nearly reſemble by their Ignorance and Confidence, that they have nothing but the Name of the College to diſtinguiſh them. Theſe are they that Aſſume to themſelves the Sole Government of that Society, and admit whom they pleaſe for Money, without Examination, and however otherwiſe unqualified; but exclude others that are Regularly admitted Doctors. This is the miſerable state of the College at preſent, in which ſuch men bear Rule, who (by the Confederacy of ſome Doctors of our own Univerſities whom they have cullied into their Cabal) have erected and eſtabliſhed a
Scandalous Monopoly of Phyſick, to the great Diſhonour of the Profeſſion, Detriment of the Univerſities, and infinite Prejudice of Mens Lives. Now the College being at preſent made up of ſo many Foreign, and ſo few Legal and truly Honourable Doctors of our own Univerſities, and the miſchief ſtill ſpreading further, ſo that in time there are like to be none (but what have taken their Degrees Abroad, or of their Cabal) allowed by their Monopoly to practiſe Phyſick, or by them owned to be Phyſicians: It is therefore thought convenient, for preventing this growing evil, to preſent the World with a true Catalogue of the Doctors in Phyſick of our Two Univerſities, diligently and carefully collected out of the Regiſters of Oxford and Cambridge, thatſo by examining the Catalogue of their College (ſo often Printed and diſperſed about the Town) with theſe of our Univerſities, every one may be able to diſtinguiſh the Legal and truly Honourable Phyſicians, from the Baſe, Illegitimate, Domineering By-blows of Aeſculapius; and that they finding themſelves detected, may be aſhamed of their proceedings, and good Men be encouraged to take their Degrees Regularly at Home in our own Univerſities.

div.head: ADVERTISEMENT.
div.p: THE Monopoly of Phyſick in Warwicklane, Vulgarly called the College, at preſent conſiſts of 73 Fellows (formerly 40) 5 Candidates, 11 Honorary Fellows, and 40 Licentiates, in all 129, ſeveral of which are no Doctors, and ſcarce 40 Regular Doctors, either in Oxford or Cambridge; which Augmentation of Fellows was begun in the late King James's time, by Vertue of his Gracious Charter, as they call it Twice in a Paper, Publiſhed by them in the Year 1688, with this Title;
His Moſt Sacred MAJESTIES, To His Moſt Honourable Privy Councils LETTERS, Relating to the College of Phyſicians.
Which Title, we leave to the Engliſh Reader to make ſenſe of if he can, And then let him try to find truth in the Paper.
